{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8a483fa9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Quantum error correction"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cef2a970",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The power of quantum computing comes from generalising the notion of a classical bit to a _qubit_. A classical bit is a system with a binary attribute, such as a light switch that is either off (0) or on (1). At any given time, the system occupies exactly one of the two states, 0 or 1. \n",
    "\n",
    "A qubit differs crucially from a classical bit. It is not a piece of information that lives in a discrete state 0 or 1, but one that can exist as a linear combination of the two states and only under measurement does in live in one of the states 0 or 1. In particular, a qubit is a physical system with a measurement operator such that the following hold:\n",
    "- Prior to measurement the state of the system can be represented by a unit vector in two-dimensional complex space.\n",
    "- When measured the system yields one of two binary outcomes.\n",
    "\n",
    "Note from a mathematical point of view, a classical bit is simply a special case of a qubit that is always confined to the states 0 and 1."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bfbf18a2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<div style=\"border:2px solid #7c3aed; border-radius:8px; max-width:95%; margin:auto; overflow:hidden;\">\n",
    "\n",
    "<div style=\"padding:8px 12px;\">\n",
    "Example. Spin states.\n",
    "</div>\n",
    "\n",
    "<div style=\"max-width:95%; justify-content:center; padding:12px; margin:0; line-height:1.6;\">\n",
    "\n",
    "The Stern-Gerlach experiment passes atoms through a special magnetic field and their resulting positions detected on a screen. The atoms accumulate in exactly two distinct locations, conventionally referred to as _spin up_ and _spin down_. That is, after measurement the experiment has two possible outcomes. Therefore, this system appears to be analogous to a classical bit. However, there is one fundamental difference.\n",
    "\n",
    "The crucial difference between a bit and a qubit is what happens _before_ measurement. In the classical situation, the light switch is always either on or off even when it is unobserved. In contrast, prior to being detected on the screen, an atom is not necessarily in a _spin up_ or _spin down_ state. Instead, it is in a state that combines both possibilities and only upon measurement does the atom collapse to one of the two outcomes. More precisely, it is a linear combination of the two states spin up and spin down. Mathematically, this is notion is familiar: a state is a vector. In particular, the state is a directional vector in three-dimensional space. Interactions with other physical objects, like the electromagnetic fields, change this state continuously, for example by rotating it. But it's value is not known until it is measured.\n",
    "\n",
    "</div>\n",
    "</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cfbdf15d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Modelling quantum states"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0bface7a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Quantum systems are modelled using a Hilbert space $H$. In the finite dimensional case, a Hilbert space is simply a complex inner product space. In an $n$-dimensional Hilbert space $H$, for vectors \n",
    "$$u = (u_1,u_2,\\dots,u_n) \\;\\; \\text{ and } \\;\\; v=(v_1,v_2,\\dots,v_n),$$\n",
    "the inner product is defined by\n",
    "$$\\langle u \\vert v \\rangle = \\sum_{i=1}^n u_i^\\ast v_i$$\n",
    "where $\\ast$ denotes complex conjugation.\n",
    "\n",
    "If we view column vectors as matrices of dimension $n \\times 1$, this inner product can be written using matrix multiplication as\n",
    "$$ \\langle u \\vert v \\rangle = (u^\\ast)^T v$$\n",
    "where $T$ denotes matrix transposition. The conjugate transpose of a matrix $M$ is denoted by $M^\\dagger = (M^\\ast)^T$.\n",
    "\n",
    "This notation leads to the bra ket formalism used in quantum mechanices. For a vector $u \\in H$, the ket $\\lvert u \\rangle$ denotes the corresponding column vector, while the bra $\\langle u \\rvert$ denotes its conjugate transpose, that is $\\langle u \\rvert = u^\\dagger$. With this notation the inner product becomes matrix multiplication\n",
    "$$ \\langle u \\vert v \\rangle = \\langle u \\rvert \\lvert v \\rangle.$$\n",
    "\n",
    "A bra $\\langle u \\rvert$ is a $1 \\times n$ matrix and a ket $\\lvert v \\rangle$ is a $n \\times 1$ matrix. Therefore, the product $\\lvert v \\rangle \\langle u \\rvert$ is also well defined, it is an $n \\times n$ matrix with entries\n",
    "$$\\lvert v \\rangle \\langle u \\rvert = (v_i u_j^\\ast)_{i,j \\in [n]}.$$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "84e11ab9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Qubits"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fc500637",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can create predefined and random qubits using the IBM Qiskit package as follows."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 108,
   "id": "f8b59f1a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "state_0 = Statevector([1.+0.j, 0.+0.j],\n",
      "            dims=(2,))\n",
      "state_1 = Statevector([0.+0.j, 1.+0.j],\n",
      "            dims=(2,))\n",
      "state_ab = Statevector([0.54433105+0.27216553j, 0.40824829-0.68041382j],\n",
      "            dims=(2,))\n",
      "random_state = Statevector([ 0.6252533+0.57846604j, -0.5220571+0.04349407j],\n",
      "            dims=(2,))\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "from qiskit.quantum_info import Statevector, random_statevector\n",
    "\n",
    "# standard basis states\n",
    "state_0 = Statevector.from_label('0')\n",
    "state_1 = Statevector.from_label('1')\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"state_0 = {state_0}\")\n",
    "print(f\"state_1 = {state_1}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# create a specific qubit\n",
    "a = 0.4 + 0.2j\n",
    "b = 0.3 - 0.5j\n",
    "norm_vec_ab = [a,b]/np.linalg.norm([a,b])\n",
    "state_ab = Statevector(norm_vec_ab)\n",
    "print(f\"state_ab = {state_ab}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# create a random qubit\n",
    "random_state = random_statevector(2)\n",
    "print(f\"random_state = {random_state}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ef76eab7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To make the print statement clearer, we define a function `pretty_state`that takes a statevector and rewrites it in standard bra ket notation. The function includes an optional argument `dp` that sets the number of decimal places used when rounding amplitudes. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "f035ceb8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "state_0 = (1.0 + 0.0j) |0⟩\n",
      "state_1 = (1.0 + 0.0j) |1⟩\n",
      "state_ab (to 3dp) = (0.544 + 0.272j) |0⟩ + (0.408 + -0.68j) |1⟩\n",
      "random_state (to 3dp) = (-0.93 + 0.093j) |0⟩ + (-0.349 + -0.073j) |1⟩\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import math\n",
    "\n",
    "def pretty_state(state, dp: int | None = None):\n",
    "    terms = []\n",
    "    state = state.data\n",
    "    bin_length = int(math.log2(len(state)))\n",
    "    for idx, amp in enumerate(state):\n",
    "        if abs(amp) > 0:\n",
    "            basis = bin(idx)[2:].zfill(bin_length)\n",
    "            \n",
    "            a = amp.real\n",
    "            b = amp.imag\n",
    "\n",
    "            if dp:\n",
    "                a = round(a, dp)\n",
    "                b = round(b, dp)\n",
    "\n",
    "            terms.append(f\"({a} + {b}j) |{basis}⟩\")\n",
    "    return \" + \".join(terms)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"state_0 = {pretty_state(state_0, 3)}\")\n",
    "print(f\"state_1 = {pretty_state(state_1, 3)}\")\n",
    "print(f\"state_ab (to 3dp) = {pretty_state(state_ab, 3)}\")\n",
    "print(f\"random_state (to 3dp) = {pretty_state(random_state, 3)}\")\n"
   ]
  },
