    "### Hermitian Unitary Errors\n",
    "\n",
    "Bit flips are only one example of unitary errors. In general, we need a method to correct all unitary errors. We start by focusing on Hermitian unitary errors, because in this case we can again adapt the classical repetition code to do quantum error correction.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let $U$ be a Hermitian unitary operator. If $U$ is a scalar multiple of the identity matrix, then it only acts by a global phase on a qubit. This has no physical effect on the measurements of the qubit and thus this operator does not induce errors on a computation. Therefore, we do not need to detect nor correct an action by this operator and we assume that $U$ is not a multiple of the identity. \n",
    "\n",
    "Since $U$ is both Hermitian and unitary its eigenvalues are real and have modulus $1$. Hence the eigenvalues are $+1$ and $-1$. Let $v_+$ and $v_-$ denote the eigenvectors of $+1$ and $-1$ respectively. Note that because $U$ is Hermitian and unitary these eigenvectors form an orthonormal basis.\n",
    "\n",
    "Define the states\n",
    "$$ \\lvert +_U \\rangle = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\left( \\lvert v_+ \\rangle + \\lvert v_- \\rangle \\right) \\;\\; \\text{ and } \\;\\; \\lvert -_U \\rangle = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\left( \\lvert v_+ \\rangle - \\lvert v_- \\rangle \\right).$$\n",
    "Then by linearity we have\n",
    "$$ U \\lvert +_U \\rangle = \\lvert -_U \\rangle \\text{ and } U\\lvert -_U \\rangle = \\lvert +_U \\rangle. $$\n",
    "In particular, $U$ flips the two states $\\lvert +_U \\rangle$ and $\\lvert -_U \\rangle$. That is, $U$ acts like a bit flip in the basis $\\left\\{ \\lvert +_U \\rangle, \\lvert -_U \\rangle \\right\\}$. \n",
    "\n",
    "This property lets us treat Hermitian unitary errors as bit flip errors after an appropriate change of basis. Therefore, we can apply the same repetition code and parity check ideas from before.\n",
    "\n",
    "Before transmission we encode our qubit using CNOT gates as before to transform\n",
    "$$\\lvert \\psi \\rangle = \\alpha \\lvert 0 \\rangle + \\beta \\lvert 1 \\rangle$$\n",
    "into\n",
    "$$\\lvert \\psi \\rangle_{\\mathrm{L}} = \\alpha \\lvert 000 \\rangle + \\beta \\lvert 111 \\rangle.$$\n",
    "Then we apply the basis change \n",
    "$$M_U = \\lvert +_U \\rangle \\langle 0 \\rvert + \\lvert -_U \\rangle \\langle 1 \\rvert$$\n",
    "to obtain\n",
    "$$M_U \\lvert \\psi \\rangle_{\\mathrm{L}} = \\alpha \\lvert +_U+_U+_U \\rangle + \\beta \\lvert -_U-_U-_U \\rangle.$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose that a $U$ error occurs on the first qubit in $M_U \\lvert \\psi \\rangle_{\\mathrm{L}}$. Then the received qubit would be\n",
    "$$\\lvert \\phi \\rangle = (U \\otimes I \\otimes I) M_U \\lvert \\psi \\rangle_{\\mathrm{L}}  = \\alpha \\lvert -_U+_U+_U \\rangle + \\beta \\lvert +_U-_U-_U \\rangle.$$\n",
    "We convert back to the standard basis to obtain\n",
    "$$M_U^{-1} \\lvert \\phi \\rangle = \\alpha \\lvert 100 \\rangle + \\beta \\lvert 011 \\rangle.$$\n",
    "Thus, we have reinterpreted the $U$ error as a bit flip in the standard basis. \n",
    "\n",
    "Now we procede as in the bit flip error correction case. We add two ancilla qubits $\\lvert 00 \\rangle$ and apply the same CNOT parity check circuit as for the bit flip code. As before this will produce the syndrome $\\lvert 10 \\rangle$ indicating an error has occured on the first qubit. Thus, we can fix this error by applying the gate\n",
    "$$U \\otimes I \\otimes I$$\n",
    "to $\\phi$, where $U$ is in the first entry because we know an error has occured on the first qubit. This results in \n",
    "$$(U \\otimes I \\otimes I) \\lvert \\phi \\rangle = \\alpha \\lvert +_U+_U+_U \\rangle + \\beta \\lvert -_U-_U-_U \\rangle;$$\n",
    "namely the original encoded message $M_U \\lvert \\psi \\rangle_{\\mathrm{L}}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "The circuit for this error correction is given by:"
   ]
