   "source": [
    "### Phase flip errors\n",
    "\n",
    "One example of a unitary Hermitian operator is the Pauli operator \n",
    "$$ Z = \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\\\ 0 & -1 \\end{pmatrix}$$\n",
    "which acts on the standard basis by\n",
    "$$ \\lvert 0 \\rangle \\mapsto \\lvert 0 \\rangle \\;\\; \\text{ and } \\;\\; \\lvert 1 \\rangle \\mapsto - \\lvert 1 \\rangle.$$\n",
    "In particular, the eigenvectors of $Z$ are the standard basis vectors. The $Z$ error is known as a phase flip since it only changes the relative phase of a qubit. Indeed, for amplitudes $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$ we have\n",
    "$$Z( \\alpha \\lvert 0 \\rangle + \\beta \\lvert 1 \\rangle ) = \\alpha \\lvert 0 \\rangle - \\beta \\lvert 1 \\rangle. $$\n",
    "Using the previous notation we can create a positive and negative state with respect to $Z$ by\n",
    "$$ \\lvert +_Z \\rangle = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} \\left(\\lvert 0 \\rangle + \\lvert 1 \\rangle \\right) = \\lvert + \\rangle \\;\\; \\text{ and } \\;\\; \\lvert -_Z \\rangle = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} \\left(\\lvert 0 \\rangle - \\lvert 1 \\rangle \\right) = \\lvert - \\rangle.$$\n",
    "Therefore, the change of basis matrix $M_Z$ is given by\n",
    "$$ M_U = \\lvert + \\rangle \\langle 0 \\rvert + \\lvert - \\rangle \\langle 1 \\rvert = H$$\n",
    "which is the Hadamard gate\n",
    "$$ H = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 \\\\ 1 & -1 \\end{pmatrix}.$$"
   ]
