   "source": [
    "Notice that the barriers on the diagram are not physically needed; they are used to separate the basis change, first parity check, second parity check and then the final basis change. In practice, as long as we preserve the order of the gates acting on each individual qubit, we are free to regroup these operations as we like.\n",
    "\n",
    "In particular, consider the operations involving the first qubit. It is acted on by a Hadamard gate, a controlled $Z$ gate that is controlled on the ancilla qubit $3$, and then another Hadamard gate. We can simplify this action by extending the identity $HZH = X$ to the controlled gates. We have already seen that\n",
    "$$ (H_0 \\otimes I_3) (\\mathrm{CZ}_{3 \\to 0}) (H_0 \\otimes I_3) = (\\mathrm{CNOT}_{3 \\to 0}).$$\n",
    "Therefore, we can replace the two Hadamard gates and the control $Z$ gate attached to the first qubit by a single CNOT gate. \n",
    "\n",
    "Applying this replacement to each control $Z$ gate that is surrounded by Hadamard gates removes repeated basis changes and yields an equivalent circuit with fewer gates but the same output."
   ]
