   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Stabilizers\n",
    "\n",
    "This interpretation gives us another way to work with error correction via group theory and group actions. \n",
    "\n",
    "The repetition code has parity check equations\n",
    "$$ P_1 = v_1 + v_2 \\;\\; \\text{ and } P_2 = v_2 + v_3.$$\n",
    "Each parity check can be represented by a binary vector given by\n",
    "$$ h_1 = \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix} \\;\\; \\text{ and } \\;\\; h_2 = \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 & 1 \\end{pmatrix} $$\n",
    "respectively. We can define two tensor operators\n",
    "$$ Z^{P_1} = Z^{h_1} = Z \\otimes Z \\otimes I \\;\\; \\text{ and } \\;\\; Z^{P_2} = Z^{h_2} = I \\otimes Z \\otimes Z. $$\n",
    "\n",
    "Now let $b = ijk$ be a binary string and consider the computational basis state $\\lvert b \\rangle = \\lvert ijk \\rangle$. Then\n",
    "$$ Z^{P_1} \\lvert b \\rangle = (Z \\otimes Z \\otimes I) \\lvert ijk \\rangle = \\lvert Z(i)Z(j)k \\rangle.$$\n",
    "Recall that\n",
    "$$ Z \\lvert 0 \\rangle = 1 \\cdot \\lvert 0 \\rangle = (-1)^0 \\lvert 0 \\rangle \\;\\; \\text{ and } \\;\\; Z \\lvert 1 \\rangle = -1 \\cdot \\lvert 1 \\rangle = (-1)^1 \\lvert 1 \\rangle.$$\n",
    "Thus, it follows that\n",
    "$$ Z^{P_1} \\lvert ijk \\rangle = \\lvert Z(i)Z(j)k \\rangle = (-1)^{i}(-1)^{j} \\lvert ijk \\rangle = (-1)^{i+j} \\lvert ijk \\rangle .$$\n",
    "In particular, the power of $-1$ in this equation is $P_1(b) = i+j$. So, we have\n",
    "$$ Z^{P_1} \\lvert b \\rangle = (-1)^{P_1(v)} \\lvert b \\rangle .$$\n",
    "Therefore, a binary string $b$ satisfies the parity check $P_1$ if and only if \n",
    "$$ P_1(b) = 0,$$\n",
    "if and only if \n",
    "$$ Z^{P_1} \\lvert b \\rangle = (-1)^{0} \\lvert b \\rangle = \\lvert b \\rangle$$\n",
    "and $\\lvert b \\rangle$ is stabilized by $Z^{P_1}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "This generalises naturally. In particular, the Pauli operators $\\mathcal{P}^{\\otimes n}$ is a group with a natural action on the set of $n$ qubits. This structure can be used to define a wide class of quantum codes known as stabilizer codes."
   ]
